  "prompt": "How can you determine the variable cost ratio formula?",
  "response": "The variable cost ratio is a financial metric that helps in understanding the proportion of variable costs in relation to total sales revenue. It can be calculated using the following formula:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Variable Cost Ratio} = \\frac{\\text{Total Variable Costs}}{\\text{Total Sales Revenue}} \\times 100\n\\]\n\n### Steps to Determine the Variable Cost Ratio:\n\n1. **Identify Total Variable Costs**: \n   - Variable costs are costs that change in relation to the level of production or sales activity. Examples include direct materials, direct labor, and variable manufacturing overhead. Gather the total variable costs incurred during a specific period.\n\n2. **Calculate Total Sales Revenue**: \n   - This is the total income generated from sales of goods or services before any costs are deducted. You can find this from your sales records.\n\n3. **Insert Values into the Formula**: \n   - Once you have the total variable costs and total sales revenue, you can plug these numbers into the formula.\n\n4. **Calculate and Interpret**:\n   - Perform the calculation to find the variable cost ratio. A higher ratio indicates that a larger portion of sales is consumed by variable costs, which can be useful for pricing and profitability analysis.\n\n### Example:\n\n- **Total Variable Costs**: $150,000\n- **Total Sales Revenue**: $500,000\n\nUsing the formula:\n\n\\[\n\\text{Variable Cost Ratio} = \\frac{150,000}{500,000} \\times 100 = 30\\%\n\\]\n\nIn this example, 30% of the sales revenue is made up of variable costs.\n\n### Conclusion:\n\nUnderstanding and calculating the variable cost ratio is useful for forecasting, budgeting, and making informed decisions about pricing and production levels.",
